or Multilingual and Multicultural Settings -- tPart 3: Research Directions in Diverse Contexts -- tChapter 12. Multilingual Researcher Identities: Interpreting Linguistically and Culturally Diverse Classrooms -- tChapter 13. Negotiating Teacher-Researcher Collaboration in Immersion Education -- tChapter 14. Languages in the Classroom: Institutional Discourses and Users’ Experiences -- tChapter 15. Bringing Home and Community to School: Institutional Constraints and Pedagogic Possibilities0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA critical reality of contemporary education in a globalised world is the growing cultural, racial and linguistic diversity in schools and the issues involved in educating increasing numbers of students who are still learning the dominant language. This poses extraordinary challenges for second and foreign language teachers in many countries, where such students must engage with the mainstream curriculum in a new language. What do these increasingly plurilingual and multicultural classrooms look like? And how do language teachers address the challenges of such diverse classrooms? This book brings together a group of well-recognised language education scholars who present their research in a range of international settings. They focus on the key areas of pedagogy, language policy and curriculum and exemplify new research directions in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Secondary)xForeign speakers. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Secondary)zUnited States. 0aLanguage arts (Secondary)xSocial aspects. 0aLiteracyxSocial aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aclassroom interaction.  acultural diversity.  aglobalisation.  al